:::summary
Socrates (c. 470–399 BC) was an Athenian philosopher widely regarded as the founder of Western philosophy. He wrote nothing himself, yet his influence — preserved through the dialogues of his student Plato — transformed how humanity thinks about ethics, knowledge, and the good life. He was condemned to death by Athens for impiety and corrupting the youth, choosing to die rather than abandon his philosophical mission.
:::

